module.exports = {"pathContext":{"posts":[{"html":"<h2>Compiler Flags</h2>\n<p>With the <code>+PrintCompilation</code> flag, information about compilation of each method is print in the console:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-bash\">java -XX:+PrintCompilation main.Main 10\n</code></pre>\n<p>Compilation information can otherwise be directed to a file with:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-bash\">java -XX:+UnlockDiagnosticVMOptions -XX:+LogCompilation main.Main 5000\n</code></pre>\n<p>Available and used code cache sizes can be print with:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-bash\">java -XX:+PrintCodeCache main.Main 10\n</code></pre>\n<p>Parameters for dynamic code cache allocation can be set with 3 flags : InitialCodeCacheSize, ReservedCodeCacheSize and CodeCacheExpansionSize. </p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-bash\">java -XX:InitialCodeCacheSize=28m -XX:+PrintCodeCache main.Main 10\n</code></pre>\n<p>Flags <code>-client</code>, <code>-server</code> and <code>-d64</code> can be use to specify whether to use the 32 bit or the 64 bit compiler. However this is not always relevant, depending on the OS and on the hardware.</p>","id":"/home/nicolas/projects/workshop/src/pages/2026-03-21-java-performance-and-memory/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark","frontmatter":{"date":"2026-03-21T14:10:00.000Z","path":"/java-performance-and-memory","title":"Java Performance and Memory","excerpt":"","tags":["java","performance","memory"]}}],"tagName":"performance"}}


